2":"1375–1472","1397–1460":"1397–1460","1435":"1435","1377":"1377","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Wooley, Sedgemoor, Somerset, England":"Sedgemoor, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Piper","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southern): occupational name for a player on the pipes, Middle English <i>pipere</i>, sometimes a paid town musician.","English: sometimes a variant of   Peppard  .","English: perhaps occasionally an occupational name from late Middle English <i>piper</i> ‘repairer or layer of pipes; plumber’."],"variants":[{"name":"Peppard","meanings":["Irish and English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>pipart</i>, <i>pippart</i> ‘piper’, a derivative of Old French <i>piper</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>pipper</i> ‘to play the pipe(s) or flute’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 12th century and is associated particularly with County Louth."]},{"name":"Pyper","meanings":["Scottish, Irish and English: variant of   Piper  . This form of the surname is found mainly in Scotland and Ireland.","Dutch: variant, archaic or Americanized, of <b>Pijper</b>, itself a variant of   Piper  ."]},{"name":"Pieper","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Hans, Alois, Armin, Bernhard, Ernst, Fritz, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz.","North German and Dutch: occupational name for a piper, a town musician, from Middle Low German <i>piper</i>, Middle Dutch <i>pi(j)per</i>. Compare   Piper   4 and German   Pfeiffer  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Pipar</b>: nickname or occupational name derived from <i>pipa</i> ‘pipe (for smoking)’."]}]},{"name":"Allice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Allice Piper was born in 1377, in Sedgemoor, Somerset, England. She married William Wheatley in 1395, in Sedgemoor, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1435, in her hometown, at the age of 58, and was buried in Sedgemoor, Somerset, England."},"et":{"1377–1435":"1377–1435","1375–1472":"1375–1472","1397–1460":"1397–1460","1435":"1435","1377":"1377","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Wooley, Sedgemoor, Somerset, England":"Sedgemoor, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1377–1435":"1377–1435","1375–1472":"1375–1472","1397–1460":"1397–1460","1435":"1435","1377":"1377","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","Wooley, Sedgemoor, Somerset, England":"Sedgemoor, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"1377–1435":"1377–1435","1375–1472":"1375–1472","1397–1460":"1397–1460","1435":"1435","1377":"1377",